  "note_text": "S: The patient is a 47-year-old female presenting with a 2-day history of sore throat accompanied by fever and painful swallowing. She reports swollen glands in the neck and white patches on her tonsils. There is a known recent exposure to strep throat from her son last week. She denies cough, nasal congestion, difficulty breathing, or severe pain limiting swallowing.\n\nO: Phone-only encounter; no physical exam or vitals available.\n\nA: The clinical presentation is consistent with streptococcal pharyngitis given the fever, tonsillar exudates, tender cervical lymphadenopathy, and known exposure to a confirmed case.\nDifferential:\n1. Streptococcal pharyngitis\n2. Viral pharyngitis\n3. Infectious mononucleosis\n4. Other bacterial pharyngitis\n\nP: - First-line medication: Azithromycin 500 mg orally on day 1, then 250 mg orally daily on days 2 through 5 (Physician must verify medication/dosing)\n- Alternatives: Clindamycin 300 mg orally three times daily for 10 days (Physician must verify medication/dosing)\n- Medication safety considerations: Patient has a penicillin allergy; avoid beta-lactam antibiotics. Monitor for gastrointestinal side effects with macrolides and clindamycin. Other contraindications not assessed in this telephone encounter.\n- Follow-up recommendations: Seek in-person medical care urgently if difficulty breathing, severe throat pain, inability to swallow liquids, or worsening symptoms develop. Seek emergency care if airway obstruction or severe systemic symptoms occur.\n- Testing: Recommend rapid antigen detection test or throat culture for confirmation of streptococcal infection if feasible."
